 Jewish economic activity-the making and selling of liquor, wine, and beer-and reveals that alcohol commerce played a crucial role in Jewish immigrant acculturation and the growth of Jewish communities in the United States. But prohibition's triumph cast a pall on American Jews' history in the alcohol trade, forcing them to revise, clarify, and defend their communal and civic identities, both to their fellow Americans and to themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aAlcoholxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aAlcoholic beverage industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aAlcoholic beverage industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewsxAlcohol usezUnited StatesxAttitudes. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814744093423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814744093.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK